      "definitions": [
        {
          "term": "Temporal Horizon",
          "definition": "The maximum future timespan an intelligence can meaningfully plan for and act upon."
        },
        {
          "term": "Timescale Decoupling",
          "definition": "The separation between an intelligence's processing speed and the temporal scale of the problems it addresses."
        }
      ],
      "invariants": [
        "Intelligence that cannot persist beyond its planning horizon will always underperform relative to one that can.",
        "The set of exploitable processes grows monotonically with the intelligence's effective temporal horizon.",
        "No finite-speed intelligence can simultaneously optimize across all timescales without hierarchical decomposition."
      ],
      "claims": [
        "The upper bound on intelligence is constrained more by temporal persistence than by computational speed.",
        "Human cognitive timescales represent an arbitrary point in the space of possible intelligence speeds, not a natural optimum.",
        "Any intelligence limited to human timescales is blind to the majority of causal structure in the universe."
      ],
      "examples": [
        "The Long Now Foundation's 10,000-Year Clock, designed to tick once per year and chime once per millennium, embodies engineering for trans-human timescales and forces confrontation with deep-time planning constraints.",
        "Radioactive waste repositories like Finland's Onkalo facility must communicate danger across 100,000 years, requiring intelligence about semiotics and material science that transcends any single language or culture."
      ],
