    "id": "dtu_459_eternal_maintenance_civilizations",
    "tier": "core",
    "tags": [
      "stsvk_459",
      "eternal",
      "maintenance",
      "civilizations"
    ],
    "human": {
      "summary": "Eternal maintenance civilizations are societies whose primary productive activity is the ongoing repair, renewal, and upkeep of existing systems, having reached a state where new construction is unnecessary and persistence itself becomes the central challenge and art.",
      "bullets": [
        "Maintenance civilizations allocate the majority of their resources to repair and renewal rather than production of new artifacts.",
        "The skill set and value system of a maintenance civilization differs fundamentally from that of a growth civilization.",
        "Eternal maintenance requires solving the motivation problem: sustaining commitment to repetitive care work across unlimited timescales."
      ]
    },
    "core": {
      "definitions": [
        {
          "term": "Maintenance Civilization",
          "definition": "A civilizational mode where the primary economic and social activity is the repair and renewal of existing systems rather than the creation of new ones."
        },
        {
          "term": "Repair Economy",
          "definition": "An economic system organized around the principle that maintaining existing value is more important than producing new value."
        }
      ],
      "invariants": [
        "All physical systems require ongoing maintenance; the question is not whether to maintain but how to sustain the will and capacity to do so.",
        "A maintenance civilization must value care, attention, and repetition as highly as a growth civilization values innovation and novelty.",
        "The transition from growth to maintenance requires a complete restructuring of incentive systems and social status hierarchies."
      ],
      "claims": [
        "Eternal maintenance is the thermodynamically inevitable end-state of any civilization that does not destroy itself through growth.",
        "The cultural contempt for maintenance work in growth-oriented societies is the single greatest risk factor for civilizational collapse.",
        "Japanese concepts of wabi-sabi and the tradition of Ise Shrine rebuilding represent existing cultural frameworks for maintenance civilization."
      ],
      "examples": [
        "The Netherlands' centuries-long dike maintenance system (Rijkswaterstaat) exemplifies eternal maintenance civilization: the nation's existence literally depends on continuous, never-complete infrastructure maintenance, producing a culture that deeply values engineering care and collective vigilance over innovation.",
        "Venice's ongoing battle against subsidence and flooding represents a city-scale maintenance civilization where the primary economic and cultural activity has shifted from trade expansion to preservation of existing structures, with the MOSE flood barrier project representing a multi-billion-euro commitment to pure maintenance."
      ],
      "nextActions": [
        "Explore dtu_446 for intelligence without progress, dtu_460 for civilization as finished artifact"
      ]
    },
    "machine": {
      "kind": "formal_model",
      "math": {
        "space": "X = (I_state, D_decay, R_repair, M_motivation) where I_state is infrastructure condition vector, D_decay is degradation rate tensor, R_repair is repair capacity, M_motivation is collective maintenance commitment level",
        "variables": {
          "x": "state",
          "u": "control",
          "w": "noise",
          "θ": "parameters"
        },
        "dynamics": "İ = -D_decay · I + R_repair · M_motivation; Ṁ = f(culture, status_of_maintenance_work) - g(boredom, repetition_fatigue); system persists iff İ ≥ 0 on average, requiring M_motivation to remain above critical threshold",
        "constraints": [
          "R_repair · M_motivation ≥ D_decay · I for all components: repair rate must exceed decay rate everywhere",
          "M_motivation ≥ M_critical: collective maintenance motivation must remain above the threshold where neglect cascades begin"
        ],
        "potential": "V(I, M) = ∑_c max(0, D_decay(c) - R_repair · M)² + (M_critical - M)² · I(M < M_critical) ≥ 0, measuring maintenance deficit plus motivation gap risk",
        "implication": "Eternal maintenance is sustainable iff the culture can generate M_motivation ≥ M_critical indefinitely; this requires that maintenance work itself be a source of meaning and status, not merely a cost center subordinate to innovation"
      },
      "primaryFormula": "MaintenanceViability(t) = min_c [R_repair(c) · M(t) / D_decay(c)] where the system fails when any component's repair-to-decay ratio drops below 1"
    },
