    "id": "dtu_470_the_map_is_not_the_territory",
    "tier": "core",
    "tags": [
      "stsvk_470",
      "the",
      "map",
      "is",
      "not",
      "territory"
    ],
    "human": {
      "summary": "The map is not the territory applies Korzybski's principle to the constraint framework itself, warning that even the most comprehensive formal model of reality is a representation, not reality, and confusing the two leads to systematic errors in reasoning and design.",
      "bullets": [
        "The constraint framework is a map of reality's structure, not the structure itself, and this distinction must be maintained at all times.",
        "Every model, no matter how accurate, omits details that may prove critical in specific applications.",
        "The framework's self-awareness of its own map-nature is what prevents it from becoming a dogma."
      ]
    },
    "core": {
      "definitions": [
        {
          "term": "Map-Territory Distinction",
          "definition": "The principle that a representation of a system is categorically different from the system itself, regardless of the representation's accuracy."
        },
        {
          "term": "Model Reification",
          "definition": "The error of treating a model's features as features of reality, confusing representational artifacts with genuine structure."
        }
      ],
      "invariants": [
        "No model can capture all features of the territory it represents; there will always be a residual between map and territory.",
        "The utility of a map depends on its appropriate level of abstraction for the task at hand, not on its total fidelity.",
        "Self-aware frameworks explicitly model the gap between themselves and reality; dogmatic frameworks deny this gap exists."
      ],
      "claims": [
        "The constraint framework avoids model reification by building the map-territory distinction into its foundational axioms.",
        "Most scientific controversies stem from confusing model features with reality features, a confusion the map-territory distinction dissolves.",
        "A framework that forgets it is a map will eventually be blindsided by aspects of reality it chose not to represent."
      ],
      "examples": [
        "A Mercator projection map distorts the sizes of landmasses near the poles, leading to the persistent misconception that Greenland is comparable in size to Africa; this is a model artifact, not a geographic fact — analogous to how interpreting wavefunction collapse literally confuses a mathematical convenience with physical reality.",
        "A climate model that accurately predicts temperature trends may represent atmospheric CO2 as a single well-mixed variable, missing localized pollution hotspots; the model is useful for its purpose but the map-territory gap becomes critical when applied to local air-quality policy."
      ],
      "nextActions": [
        "Formalize the map-territory gap metric for each domain where the framework is applied"
      ]
    },
    "machine": {
      "kind": "formal_model",
      "math": {
        "space": "M × T where M = {models/maps} and T = {territories/realities}; gap function δ: M × T → R≥0",
        "variables": {
          "x": "state",
          "u": "control",
          "w": "noise",
          "θ": "parameters"
        },
        "dynamics": "δ(m, t, s) = ||π_s(m) - π_s(t)|| — the gap at scale s between model predictions and territory observations",
        "constraints": [
          "δ(m, t) > 0 for all non-trivial models m and territories t: no model achieves zero gap",
          "∂δ/∂(abstraction level) may be positive or negative: higher abstraction can increase or decrease the gap depending on the question"
        ],
        "potential": "V(m) = E_t[δ(m, t)²] ≥ 0; expected squared gap across all territory states; the irreducible model error",
        "implication": "V(m) > 0 always; any claim that V = 0 is itself a map-territory confusion, confusing model completeness with reality capture"
      },
      "primaryFormula": "∀m ∈ M, ∀t ∈ T: δ(m, t) > 0 ∧ utility(m) = f(1/δ, abstraction_match)"
    },
