    "id": "dtu_479_from_explanation_to_design",
    "tier": "core",
    "tags": [
      "stsvk_479",
      "from",
      "explanation",
      "to",
      "design"
    ],
    "human": {
      "summary": "From explanation to design marks the pivot where the constraint framework transitions from a tool for understanding existing phenomena to a tool for designing new systems, using constraint satisfaction as a constructive principle rather than merely an analytical one.",
      "bullets": [
        "The same constraint geometry that explains why existing systems work can be used to design new systems that satisfy specified constraints.",
        "Design within the constraint framework means specifying the desired constraint satisfaction profile and then finding configurations that achieve it.",
        "This transition transforms the framework from a retrospective explanatory tool into a prospective engineering methodology."
      ]
    },
    "core": {
      "definitions": [
        {
          "term": "Constraint-Based Design",
          "definition": "The practice of designing systems by specifying the constraints they must satisfy and then searching for configurations that satisfy all constraints simultaneously."
        },
        {
          "term": "Constructive Constraint Analysis",
          "definition": "Using constraint satisfaction as a generative principle to create new systems rather than merely analyzing existing ones."
        }
      ],
      "invariants": [
        "Any framework that can explain why a system works can, in principle, be inverted to design systems that work.",
        "Design within the constraint framework guarantees that the designed system satisfies all specified constraints, provided the constraint set is consistent.",
        "The transition from explanation to design requires that the framework's constraint language be precise enough to serve as an engineering specification."
      ],
      "claims": [
        "Constraint-based design produces more robust systems than optimization-based design because it ensures all viability conditions are met, not just that a single metric is maximized.",
        "The greatest practical value of the constraint framework lies in its design applications, not in its explanatory power.",
        "Moving from explanation to design is the acid test of any theoretical framework: theories that cannot inform design are incomplete."
      ],
      "examples": [
        "Constraint-based design in architecture: specifying constraints (load-bearing capacity ≥ X, natural light ≥ Y lumens, cost ≤ Z dollars, accessibility compliance) and then searching the design space for configurations satisfying all constraints simultaneously, rather than optimizing a single aesthetic metric.",
        "The transition from explanatory evolutionary biology (why did this trait evolve?) to synthetic biology (design an organism with specified metabolic constraints) exemplifies moving from explanation to design: the same fitness-landscape theory that explains adaptation now guides the engineering of novel organisms."
      ],
      "nextActions": [
        "Develop constraint-based design methodologies for specific application domains; build design tools"
      ]
    },
    "machine": {
      "kind": "formal_model",
      "math": {
        "space": "D = {designs d ∈ R^n} with constraint set C_spec = {c_1, ..., c_m} specified by the designer",
        "variables": {
          "x": "state",
          "u": "control",
          "w": "noise",
          "θ": "parameters"
        },
        "dynamics": "d_{t+1} = d_t - α∇V(d_t) + projection onto feasible set {d : ∀i: c_i(d) ≤ 0} — gradient descent with constraint projection",
        "constraints": [
          "∀i: c_i(d*) ≤ 0 — the designed system must satisfy all specified constraints at the solution d*",
          "consistency(C_spec) = true: the constraint set itself must be satisfiable; no design can satisfy contradictory constraints"
        ],
        "potential": "V(d) = Σ_i max(0, c_i(d))² ≥ 0; V = 0 iff design d satisfies all constraints",
        "implication": "V(d*) = 0 ⟹ d* is a valid design; the framework guarantees all viability conditions are met, not just that a single metric is optimized"
      },
      "primaryFormula": "design(C_spec) = argmin_d V(d) subject to consistency(C_spec) = true"
    },
